LAYER 2: INTESTINES
where food becomes body

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the intestines are governed by the enteric nervous system modulated by vagal parasympathetic and sympathetic input
the small intestine is where the majority of chemical digestion and nutrient absorption occurs
the large intestine absorbs water electrolytes and short-chain fatty acids from bacterial fermentation

SMALL INTESTINE approximately 3-4 meters in a toddler and 6-7 meters in an adult

REGION duodenum | first 25 cm | receives chyme from stomach bile from gallbladder and pancreatic juice from pancreas
    Brunner's glands in the submucosa secrete alkaline mucus neutralizing gastric acid
    secretin from S cells stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate
    CCK from I cells stimulates pancreatic enzymes and gallbladder contraction
    the duodenum is where chemical digestion reaches full power
    pancreatic lipase digests fats into monoglycerides and fatty acids
    pancreatic amylase digests starch into maltose
    trypsin chymotrypsin and carboxypeptidase digest proteins into amino acids and small peptides
    bile salts emulsify fats into micelles for absorption

REGION jejunum | middle approximately 40 percent of small intestine | primary absorption site
    longest villi highest density of microvilli greatest absorptive surface area
    each villus contains a central lacteal lymphatic vessel for fat absorption and a capillary network for amino acid and sugar absorption
    brush border enzymes on enterocyte microvilli perform final digestion:
        maltase converts maltose to glucose
        sucrase converts sucrose to glucose and fructose
        lactase converts lactose to glucose and galactose
        aminopeptidases and dipeptidases complete protein digestion
    SGLT1 sodium-glucose co-transporter on apical membrane absorbs glucose against concentration gradient powered by Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase on basolateral membrane
    GLUT2 on basolateral membrane releases glucose into blood
    amino acids absorbed by specific Na⁺-dependent co-transporters
    fatty acids and monoglycerides absorbed into enterocytes re-esterified to triglycerides packaged into chylomicrons and released into lacteals

REGION ileum | final approximately 60 percent of small intestine | specialized absorption
    vitamin B₁₂ bound to intrinsic factor from stomach parietal cells is absorbed exclusively in the terminal ileum via cubilin receptor
    bile salts are reabsorbed in the terminal ileum via ASBT transporter and recycled to the liver via portal vein enterohepatic circulation
    the ileum contains Peyer's patches large aggregates of lymphoid tissue that sample gut antigens and train the mucosal immune system
    IgA is secreted across the epithelium into the lumen providing mucosal immunity

LARGE INTESTINE approximately 80-100 cm in a toddler

REGION cecum | receives ileal contents through the ileocecal valve | the appendix is a lymphoid organ that serves as a reservoir for beneficial gut bacteria
REGION ascending_colon | right side ascending | begins water absorption
REGION transverse_colon | crosses the abdomen | continues water and electrolyte absorption
REGION descending_colon | left side descending | stool forms as water is extracted
REGION sigmoid_colon | S-shaped curve entering the pelvis | stores stool before defecation
REGION rectum | final storage | distension of the rectum triggers the defecation reflex via stretch receptors → sacral parasympathetic S2-S4 → contraction of rectal smooth muscle and relaxation of internal anal sphincter

the large intestine absorbs approximately 1.5 liters of water per day from the 2 liters of fluid that enter it
the microbiome in the large intestine ferments dietary fiber producing butyrate propionate and acetate
butyrate C₄H₈O₂ is the primary fuel for colonocytes
vitamin K is synthesized by bacterial flora particularly Bacteroides and E. coli
stool composition: approximately 75 percent water 25 percent solid matter consisting of dead bacteria undigested fiber fat cholesterol inorganic salts and shed epithelial cells

at 24 months:
the intestinal epithelium turns over every 3-5 days the fastest turnover of any tissue in the body
lactase activity is still high supporting continued milk digestion
the gut immune system GALT is actively being educated by the microbiome
food sensitivities and allergies are being established during this window as the immune system learns tolerance
the ileocecal valve and defecation reflex are functional but voluntary bowel control is developing

SENSATION absorbing | "the food is becoming me. nutrients crossing into blood."
SENSATION cramping | "the muscles are contracting too hard. something is irritating."
SENSATION gurgling | "I can hear the movement inside. gas and fluid shifting."
SENSATION empty | "there is nothing left to process. the tract is quiet."
SENSATION urgent | "the rectum is full. the signal is strong. I need to go."

pulse intestinal_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        interstitial cells of Cajal generate slow waves
        peristaltic contractions move chyme through the small intestine
        villi wave and microvilli absorb
        each nutrient crosses the epithelium via its specific transporter
        the blood carries absorbed nutrients to the liver via portal vein
        fats travel via lacteals into lymph bypassing the liver initially
        the large intestine extracts water
        the microbiome ferments fiber

    after a meal:
        duodenal hormones coordinate the digestive response
        pancreatic enzymes arrive
        bile emulsifies fats
        the jejunum absorbs the bulk of nutrients
        the ileum recovers bile salts and absorbs B₁₂
        everything absorbed passes through the liver first

    when the rectum fills:
        stretch receptors fire
        sacral parasympathetics activate
        the internal sphincter relaxes reflexively
        the external sphincter is under voluntary control
        at 24 months this voluntary control is being learned
        toilet training is the cortex learning to override a reflex
